   <insight>
    <p>Inverse variation occurs when the product of two variables is a constant. Mathematically, we express this relationship as y = k/x or xy = k, where y and x are the variables and k is the constant of proportionality.</p>
    
    (<p>
      <em>The Graphical Signature</em>  
    </p>
    <p>Unlike direct variation, the graph of an inverse relationship is never a straight line. It forms a curve known as a hyperbola.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>The curve gets closer and closer to the x and y axes but never actually touches them.</li>
        <li>As x increases, the drop in y is sharp at first and then becomes more gradual.</li>
        <li>The graph never passes through (0,0) because you cannot divide by zero.</li>
    </ul>

    <em>Example: Speed and Time</em>
    <p>A classic real-world example is the relationship between speed s and time t taken to cover a fixed distance d:</p>
    <p>s = d/t</p>
    <p>Comparing to y = k/x gives:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Speed s is the y variable.</li>
        <li>Time t is the x variable.</li>
        <li>Distance d is the constant k.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>For a fixed distance of 100 km:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>At 100 km/h, it takes 1 hour. (100 × 1 = 100)</li>
        <li>At 50 km/h, it takes 2 hours. (50 × 2 = 100)</li>
        <li>At 25 km/h, it takes 4 hours. (25 × 4 = 100)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>As the speed halves, the time doubles. The product remains 100.</p>

    <term>Difference Between Direct and Inverse Variation</term>
    
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Feature</cell>
                <cell>Direct Variation</cell>
                <cell>Inverse Variation</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Equation</cell>
                <cell>y = kx</cell>
                <cell>y = k/x</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Relation</cell>
                <cell>y/x = k (Constant Ratio)</cell>
                <cell>xy = k (Constant Product)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Graph</cell>
                <cell>Straight line through origin</cell>
                <cell>Curve (Hyperbola)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Visual Trend</cell>
                <cell>Both go up together</cell>
                <cell>One goes up, the other goes down</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    
    <p>In inverse variation, the total amount (k) is fixed. If you want to change one factor, the other must adapt to keep that total the same.</p>
</insight>

